comments.message:
sh ?

In case bash is not installed

Given that you have set -e enabled, that command would exit the whole script if the directory doesn't exist, that's why I used the invert logic in my test:

[ ! -e "$HOME/.local/bin" ] || export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"

If the directory doesn't exist => [ ! -e "$HOME/.local/bin" ] exit with 0 so || is not executed

If the directory exist => [ ! -e "$HOME/.local/bin" ] exit with with 1 so the export PATH is executed (and exists with 0)

Sorry. I did not get the intention originally.

But the list command && will not exit the whole script here.

Reference.
From https://tiswww.case.edu/php/chet/bash/bashref.html#The-Set-Builtin,

The shell does not exit if the command that fails is part of the command list immediately following a while or until keyword, part of the test in an if statement, part of any command executed in a && or || list except the command following the final && or ||...

I've tested in my sh. 

But inverted logic will make the list command always exist 0. It's safer with set -e enabled. 

I will update it just in case other shells behaviors I was not aware of.
Change has been successfully merged by Bertrand Roussel

commits.commitMessage:
Ignore whitespace check for merge commit

Whitespace check added causing issues with 3rd party projects
Solution: Ignore whitespace checks for merge commit

Resolves: FARM-743
Change-Id: Ib182fd832377489a899c591815160f07a722ad5b
commits.subject: Ignore whitespace check for merge commit

comments.message: It is to check if this is third party code. The issue only happens with 3rd party code
Please provide some proper comment in the code

Instead of parsing through git-cat file, I think something like:

    output = _run_command(["git", "rev-list", "-n1", "--merges", commit])
    if output.rstrip() == commit:
        print("Skipping whitespace checks for merge commit.")
        return

should also work.  The advantage is parsing cat-file output risks false positive if the commit message contains the string "parent".

Alternatively, I think this check can be skipped on *all* 3rd party code, not just merge commits.

 - Your commit message should start with an upper case.
